</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>36153_1</DOCNO>
<TEXT>Millisecond

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>36153_2</DOCNO>
<TEXT>A millisecond (from milli- and second; symbol: ms) is a thousandth (0.001 or 10 or /) of a second.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>36153_3</DOCNO>
<TEXT>10 milliseconds (a hundredth of a second) are called a centisecond.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>36153_4</DOCNO>
<TEXT>100 milliseconds (one tenth of a second) are called a decisecond.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>36153_5</DOCNO>
<TEXT>To help compare orders of magnitude of different times, this page lists times between 10 seconds and 10 seconds (1 milli<nowiki>second</nowiki> and one second). "See also" times of other orders of magnitude.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>36156_1</DOCNO>
<TEXT>Microsecond

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>36156_2</DOCNO>
<TEXT>A microsecond is an SI unit of time equal to one millionth (0.000001 or 10 or /) of a second. Its symbol is μs. One microsecond is to one second as one second is to 11.574 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>36156_3</DOCNO>
<TEXT>A microsecond is equal to 1000 nanoseconds or / milliseconds. Because the next SI prefix is 1000 times larger, measurements of 10 and 10 seconds are typically expressed as tens or hundreds of microseconds. A microsecond of sound signal sample (44.1 kHz, 2 channel, 24 bit, WAV) is typically stored on 4 µm of CD, 2 bits per µs per 4 µm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>36160_1</DOCNO>
<TEXT>597

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>36160_2</DOCNO>
<TEXT>Year 597 (DXCVII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar. The denomination 597 for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the Anno Domini calendar era became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>36160_3</DOCNO>
<TEXT><onlyinclude>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>36160_4</DOCNO>
<TEXT></onlyinclude>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
